The presence of excessive fibrous connective tissue in the liver. Fibrosis is a reparative or reactive process.

A disorder characterized by replacement of the liver parenchyma with fibrous tissue and regenerative nodules. It is usually caused by alcoholism, hepatitis B, and hepatitis C. Complications include the development of ascites, esophageal varices, bleeding, and hepatic encephalopathy.
A protein-lysine 6-oxidase that is encoded in the genome of human.

A congenital disorder usually inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern. It affects the hepatobiliary system and the kidneys. It is characterized by liver fibrosis, portal hypertension, and renal cysts.
Hepatic fibrosis that reaches from a portal area to another portal area.
A proteinase-activated receptor 1 that is encoded in the genome of human.
The presence of fibrosis affecting the interlobular stroma of liver.
